Declaration:
Tells the program about the type and name of an entity (variable or function) without allocating memory.
int add(int a, int b);
  
Definition:
Allocates memory and, in the case of functions, includes the implementation.
int add(int a, int b)
  return a + b; // Function definition including the body

Implementation:
Specifically for functions, it is the detailed logic within the function's body.
return a + b;

Invocation:
The place where is function called.
add(4, 50);
